{"title_page": "Da Nang Air Base", "text_new": "{{For|the civil use of the facility|Da Nang International Airport}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n|name=Da Nang Air Base\n|ensign=[[File:Vietnam Air Force (south) roundel.svg|60px]]&nbsp;[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|60px]] \n|partof=[[Republic of Vietnam Air Force]] (RVNAF)<br>[[Pacific Air Forces]] (USAF)\n|location=\n|coordinates={{Coord|16|02|38|N|108|11|58|E|name=Danang AB|display=inline}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|map_type = Vietnam\n|map_size = 170\n|map_alt =\n|map_caption = Location of Da Nang Air Base in Vietnam\n|type=Air Force Base\n|code=\n|built=1930s\n|builder=\n|materials=\n|height=\n|used=1930s\u2013Present\n|demolished=\n|condition= Joint Civil/Military Airport\n|ownership=\n|controlledby=\n|garrison=\n|commanders=\n|occupants=\n|battles= [[World War II]]<br>[[First Indochina War]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]\n|events=\n}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| IATA = DAD\n| ICAO = VVDN\n| name = Airfield information\n| elevation-f = 33\n| elevation-m = 10\n| website =\n| r1-number = 17L/35R\n| r1-length-f = 11,483\n| r1-length-m = 3500\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| r2-number = 17R/35L\n| r2-length-f = 10,000\n| r2-length-m = 3,048\n| r2-surface = Asphalt\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Da Nang Air Base''' ({{lang-vi|C\u0103n c\u1ee9 kh\u00f4ng qu\u00e2n \u0110\u00e0 N\u1eb5ng}}) (1930s\u20131975) (also known as '''Da Nang Airfield''', '''Tourane Airfield''' or '''Tourane Air Base''') was a [[French Air Force]] and later [[Republic of Vietnam Air Force]] (RVNAF) facility located in the city of [[Da Nang]], [[Vietnam]]. During the [[Vietnam War]] (1959\u20131975), it was a major base with [[United States Army]], [[United States Air Force]] (USAF), and [[United States Marine Corps]] (USMC) units stationed there. [[Air Vietnam]] also used the facility from 1951 to 1975 for civilian domestic and international flights within Southeast Asia.\n\n==Early history==\nOn 22 September 1940, the [[Vichy France|Vichy Government]] signed an agreement with Japan allowing the Japanese to station troops in [[Tonkin]] and use three airfields there.<ref name=Logevall>{{cite book|last=Logevall|first=Fredrik|title=Embers of War: The fall of an Empire and the making of America's Vietnam|publisher=Random House|year=2012|isbn=9780375756474|page=33}}</ref> On 14 July 1941, the Japanese sent the French an ultimatum demanding the use of bases in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]] and [[Cochinchina]], the French acquiesced and by late July, the Japanese occupied [[Cam Ranh Bay]], [[Bien Hoa Air Base]] and Tourane Airfield.<ref name=Logevall/>{{rp|39\u201340}}\n\nIn late 1944, the [[Fourteenth Air Force]] based in southern China began raiding Japanese bases throughout Indochina and on 12 January 1945, the [[United States Third Fleet]] launched attacks on Japanese coastal bases including Da Nang.<ref name=Logevall/>{{rp|68\u20139}}\n\n==Indochina War (1945\u20131954)==\n[[File:Aerial view of Tourane Airfield 01 (Indochina) c1954.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Tourane Airfield in 1954]]\nTourane Airfield was used by the [[French Air Force]] during the [[First Indochina War|French Indochina War]].\n\nIn December 1950, pursuant to the [[Mutual Defense Assistance Act]] and Program, the US delivered [[Douglas A-26 Invader|B-26 Invaders]] to the French and these were used to form the [[Bombardment Group I/19 Gascogne]] based at Tourane.<ref name=Futrell>{{cite book|last=Futrell|first=Robert|title=The United States Air Force in Southeast Asia: The Advisory Years to 1965|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1981|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100525-052.pdf|isbn=9789998843523}}</ref>{{rp|7}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gouv.fr/air/activites/unites-aeriennes/escadrons-de-chasse/escadron-de-chasse-01.091-gascogne|title=Escadron de chasse 01.091 \" Gascogne \"|publisher=French MoD|accessdate=3 May 2016|language=French}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, the US [[Eighteenth Air Force]] [[Fairchild C-119 Flying Boxcar|C-119s]] were deployed to Tourane to support French military operations, a number of these aircraft crewed by civilians later flew in support of French forces in the [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.18af.amc.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=19636 |title=18TH AIR FORCE FACT SHEET |publisher=United States Air Force |date=12 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423094112/http://www.18af.amc.af.mil//library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=19636 |archivedate=23 April 2013 }}</ref> In 1953/54 the French laid a NATO-standard {{convert|7800|ft|m|adj=on}} asphalt runway at Tourane.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|52}}\n\nIn January 1954, the USAF delivered a further 16 B-26s and 3 RB-26s to Tourane and in February assigned USAF maintenance and supply personnel to Tourane on temporary duty to support B-26 operations.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|17}} On 19 March the USAF deployed the 1808th Airways and Air Communications Service Squadron to Indochina with 60 enlisted men and one civilian at Tourane.<ref name=Williams>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Kenneth|title=The US Air Force in Southeast Asia and the Vietnam War A Narrative Chronology Volume I: The Early Years through 1959|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2019|url=https://media.defense.gov/2019/Feb/22/2002092352/-1/-1/1/USAF%20Vietnam%20Chronology%20v1.pdf|isbn=}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|117}} On 6 April the USAF delivered 11 B\u201326s to Tourane  for loan to the French.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|130}} The USAF delivered 18 [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|C-47s]] to Tourane on 9 April to replace aircraft losses.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|24}} Later in April [[VMA-324]] delivered 25 [[Vought F4U Corsair|F4U/G Corsairs]] to the French Air Force at Tourane.<ref name=Whitlow>{{cite book|last=Whitlow|first=Robert|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam:The Advisory And Combat Assistance Era, 1954\u20131964|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1977|isbn=1494285290|page=71}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the French defeat at Dien Bien Phu and in anticipation of the [[Geneva Conference (1954)|Indochina peace treaty]], on 23 May the USAF C-119 detachment at [[Cat Bi International Airport#First Indochina War|Cat Bi Air Base]] moved to Tourane.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|149}}\n\nOn 14 June 1954 [[Viet Minh]] troops captured five USAF airmen of the [[315th Air Division]] stationed at Tourane while they were on an unauthorized beach outing. They were held at a small camp about {{convert|60|mi}} south of Tourane that was ringed by mines and pits with bamboo stakes. The airmen remained in captivity until 31 August when they were released to the French as part of a prisoner exchange.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|156}}\n\nOn 19 July 1954 the USAF 6424th Air Depot Wing detachment that had supported French B\u201326 operations at Tourane completed its closeout and was inactivated.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|165}}\n\nOn 6 September the last of the B-26s and C-119s on loan to the French departed from Tourane.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|31}}\n\n==Republic of Vietnam Air Force use (1955\u20131970)==\n[[File:VNAF Skyraider at Da Nang 1967.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Republic of Vietnam Air Force|RVNAF]] [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|A-1]] at Da Nang AB in 1967]]\nBy the end of the Indochina War, the French had established a small Republic of Vietnam Air Force (RVNAF) consisting of 2 squadrons of [[Fieseler Fi 156#French production|Morane-Saulnier MS.500]] and one of [[Morane-Saulnier MS.315]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|36}} In January 1955, [[Military Assistance Advisory Group|MAAG Vietnam]] decided that the RVNAF would comprise one fighter, two liaison and two transport squadrons and that training would be undertaken by the French. Under the Mutual Defence Assistance Program, the US delivered 28 [[Grumman F8F Bearcat|F8Fs]], 35 C-47s and 60 [[O-1 Bird Dog|L-19s]] to the RVNAF to equip the planned expansion.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|49\u201350}} On 19 September 1955 the French turned over Tourane Airfield to the RVNAF, at the time the base had a {{convert|7850|ft}} runway, with potential extension of at least {{convert|1000|ft}}.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|208\u20139}} On 1 June 1957 all RVNAF training responsibility passed from the French to the United States.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|50}}\n\nIn November 1955, the RVNAF 1st Liaison Squadron moved to Da Nang AB from [[Hu\u1ebf]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|272}}\n\nIn October 1961, the 2nd Helicopter Squadron was activated at Da Nang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|273}}\n\nIn December 1961 the 3rd Liaison Squadron was activated at Da Nang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|273}}\n\nIn mid-1962, the RVNAF 2nd Fighter Squadron equipped with [[North American T-28 Trojan|T-28s]] became operational at [[Nha Trang Air Base]] and began detaching 6 aircraft to Da Nang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|132}}\n\nIn January 1963, the 2nd Helicopter Squadron was redesignated the 213th Helicopter Squadron, the 1st Liaison Squadron was redesignated the 110th Liaison Squadron and the 3rd Liaison Squadron was redesignated the 114th Liaison Squadron.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|273}}\n\nIn February 1964, the 516th Fighter Squadron equipped with 15 [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|A-1 Skyraiders]] moved to Da Nang AB from Nha Trang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|274}} On 15 March 1964 the RVNAF established a Tactical Wing Headquarters at the base.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|211}} In May the 217th Helicopter Squadron was established at the base.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|274}}\n\nOn 8 February 1965, RVNAF commander [[Nguy\u1ec5n Cao K\u1ef3]] led VNAF A-1s from the base on a [[Operation Flaming Dart|retaliatory raid against North Vietnamese targets]].<ref name=Schlight>{{cite book|last=Schlight|first=John|title=The United States Air Force in Southeast Asia: The War in South Vietnam The Years of the Offensive 1965\u20131968|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1999|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-101013-038.pdf|isbn=9780912799513|page=60}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 1965, 20 A-1s from the base participated in the first attacks of [[Operation Rolling Thunder]], striking the [[Vietnam People's Navy]] base at [[Qu\u1ea3ng Kh\u00ea]].<ref name=Van>{{cite book|last=Van Staaveren|first=Jacob|title=Gradual Failure: The Air War over North Vietnam 1965\u20131966|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2002|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100526-034.pdf|isbn=9781508779094|page=84}}</ref> On 14 March the VNAF led by General K\u1ef3 participated in attacks on barracks on H\u00f2n Gi\u00f3 island.<ref name=Van/>{{rp|85}}\n\nIn August 1965, 4 USAF [[Martin B-57 Canberra|B-57Bs]] operating from the base were nominally transferred to the RVNAF becoming their first jet aircraft.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|88}}\n\nIn 1970, the RVNAF units at Da Nang AB were reorganized as the First Air Division with responsibility for [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|Military Region I]].<ref name=Nalty>{{cite book|last=Nalty|first=Bernard|title=The United States Air Force in Southeast Asia: The War in South Vietnam Air War over South Vietnam 1968\u20131975|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2000|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100924-004.pdf|isbn=9781478118640|page=213}}</ref> Also during that year the RVNAF began building family housing at the base for its personnel.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|214}}\n\n==United States military use (1962\u20131972)==\nDa Nang Air Base was used as a primary entry point for American service members flying into Vietnam fighting in the Vietnam War. It was used by the United States Marine Corps (USMC) as well as the US Air force (USAF).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hoffman |first1=David |title=Interview - Bill Ehrhart (Making sense of the sixties) |url=https://ew.com/article/1991/01/18/making-sense-sixties/ |website=www.wdehrhart.com |publisher=Hoffman and Ehrhart |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===US Army use===\nFrom January 1962 until September the [[93rd Transportation Company (Light Helicopter)]] with [[Piasecki H-21|Piasecki CH-21C Shawnee's]] was based here.<ref name=Dunstan>{{cite book|last=Dunstan|first=S|title=Vietnam Choppers|year=1988|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd|isbn=0-85045-572-3}}</ref>{{rp|20}} During February the company was joined by the [[339th Transportation Company (Direct Support)]]. In September 1962, the CH-21's left and were replaced by [[VMM-362|HMM-362]] with the [[611th Transportation Company (Aircraft Direct Support)]].<ref name=Dunstan/>{{rp|21}}\n\n===USAF use===\n[[File:F-100Ds 416TFS DaNang 1965.jpg|thumb|right|250px|F-100Ds of the [[416th Fighter Squadron]] at Da Nang AB in 1965]]\n[[File:64th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron Convair F-102A-75-CO Delta Dagger 56-1333 Da Nang 1966.jpg|thumb|right|250px|64th FIS F-102A landing at Da Nang AB, 1966]]\n[[File:Danang Air Field, September 1966 (17087464072).jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Northwest Airlines]] [[Boeing 707]] at Da Nang AB in September 1966]]\n[[File:Da Nang Air Base during the Vietnam War.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Da Nang AB in the late 1960s]]\n[[File:37th ARRSq Revetments, DaNang, RVN 1970-71.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron|37th ARRS]] [[Sikorsky MH-53|HH-53s]] at Da Nang AB c.1970]]\nIn January 1962, the USAF [[5th Tactical Control Group]] was deployed to Da Nang AB to provide air support operations in [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|I Corps]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|106}} By 2 March [[Fairchild C-123 Provider|C-123s]] were stationed at the base under [[Project Mule Train]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|108}} On 20 May 1962 the 6222nd Air Base Squadron was formed at the base to support VNAF operations and the growing USAF presence through [[Farm Gate (military operation)|Farm Gate]] operations.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|101}}\n\nOn 15 June 1962, 12 C-123s from the [[777th Expeditionary Airlift Squadron|777th Troop Carrier Squadron]] deployed to the base forming the Tactical Air Force Transport Squadron Provisional-2 to supplement the existing Mule Train operations and those of the US Army's 18th Fixed Wing Aviation Company equipped with [[de Havilland Canada DHC-3 Otter|U-1 Otters]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|110\u20131}}\n\nIn early 1962, the base runway was asphalt covered and {{convert|7900|ft|m|adj=on}} long while the taxiways and parking areas were covered in [[Marston Mat|Pierced steel planking]] (PSP).<ref name=Tregaskis>{{cite book|last=Tregaskis|first=Richard|title=Southeast Asia:Building the Bases, The History of Construction in Southeast Asia|publisher=U.S. Navy Seabee Museum|year=1975|url=https://www.history.navy.mil/content/dam/museums/Seabee/Online%20Reading%20Room/Manuals%20and%20Publications/Publications/Southeast%20Asia%2C%20Building%20The%20Bases%2C%20A%20History%20Of%20Const.pdf|isbn=9781461097235|page=42}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1963, the 777th Troop Carrier Squadron equipped with 16 C-123s was transferred to the base and later that year the base's existing Mule Train operations were redesignated as the [[311th Troop Carrier Squadron]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|167\u201371}}\n\nIn early 1964, the [[U.S. Navy]] [[Officer in Charge of Construction RVN]] (OICC) directed the American construction contractor [[RMK-BRJ]] to rebuild and extend the existing runway to 10,000 feet long (3,050 meters), with new asphalt paving. This was completed in July 1964.<ref name=Tregaskis/>{{rp|66}}\n\nOn 5 August 1964, following the [[Gulf of Tonkin incident]], 6 [[Convair F-102 Delta Dagger|F-102s]] from the [[509th Tactical Fighter Squadron|509th Fighter Squadron]] and 8 [[North American F-100 Super Sabre|F-100s]] from the [[615th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (615th TFS) deployed to Da Nang AB from [[Clark Air Base]] in the Philippines.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|229}} The F-100s were proposed to be used for a strike against the [[Vietnam People's Air Force]] (VPAF) [[Ph\u00fac Y\u00ean Air Base]] as part of the US response to the incident, however approval for the strike was denied.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|230\u20132}}\n\nCommencing in December 1964, Da Nang AB was used to support [[Operation Barrel Roll]], the covert air war in neighbouring Laos. On 14 December [[Republic F-105 Thunderchief|F-105s]] from the [[80th Fighter Squadron|80th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] based at [[Korat Royal Thai Air Force Base]], Thailand staged through Da Nang for the initial strikes supported by the base's F-100s. Later that month F-105s from the [[44th Fighter Squadron|44th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base for further strikes near [[Tchepone]],<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|256\u20137}} these aircraft would form Detachment 2 [[18th Wing|18th Tactical Fighter Wing]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|256\u20137}} Also in December the [[613th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nIn February 1965, 12 F-100s from the [[3d Wing|3rd Tactical Fighter Wing]] deployed to the base to support the [[Operation Flaming Dart]] airstrikes.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|274}}\n\nOn 2 March 1965, F-100s, F-105s and VNAF A-1s from the base participated in the first attacks of Operation Rolling Thunder, striking the naval base at Qu\u1ea3ng Kh\u00ea, losing 2 F-100s in the attack.<ref name=Van/>\n\nBy March 1965, with the base overcrowded by the arrival of new squadrons, a major expansion was approved. In August 1965, the OICC directed RMK-BRJ to construct a second  {{convert|10000|ft|m|adj=on}} parallel runway and paved taxiways and parking areas.<ref name=Tregaskis/>{{rp|149\u2013150}}<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|26\u20138}} The second runway opened in July 1966.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|158}}\n\nIn March 1965, the [[35th Fighter Wing|35th Tactical Fighter Wing]] (35th TFW) deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}In April the [[615th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/> The [[416th Fighter Squadron|416th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base before moving to [[Bien Hoa Air Base]] in mid-May.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} Also in April the [[476th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (476th TFS) equipped with [[Lockheed F-104 Starfighter|F-104Cs]] was deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In May the [[20th Tactical Air Support Squadron]] (20th TASS) equipped with [[Cessna O-1 Bird Dog|O-1s]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In June the 615th TFS returned to the US.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|55}} In mid-June the [[8th Special Operations Squadron|8th Bombardment Squadron]] equipped with [[Martin B-57 Canberra|B-57Bs]] moved to the base from Bien Hoa, these would be rotated with other B-57s from the [[13th Bomb Squadron|13th Bombardment Squadron]] until September 1966 when they would be moved to [[Phan Rang Air Base]].<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nOn the early morning of 1 July 1965, the PAVN and Vietcong launched a mortar and sapper attack on the base, destroying one F-102 and two [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130s]] and damaging a further two F-102s and one C-130.<ref name=Shu65>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=The Landing and the Buildup, 1965 |publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1978|isbn=1494287552|pages=56\u20137}}</ref>\n\nIn July, the [[436th Tactical Fighter Training Squadron|436th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (436th TFS) replaced the 476th TFS.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In October the [[435th Fighter Training Squadron|435th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] replaced the 436th TFS.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In November the [[390th Electronic Combat Squadron|390th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (390th TFS) equipped with [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4s]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nOn 1 January 1966, the 4503rd Tactical Fighter Squadron equipped with the [[Northrop F-5|F-5A ''Skoshi Tiger'']] moved to the base for trial operations over North Vietnam and Laos.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|89\u201390}} The F-5s returned to Bien Hoa in early February and returned to Da Nang AB from 20 February to 10 March when they returned again to Bien Hoa and were redesignated as the 10th Fighter Squadron.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|125}}\n\nOn 8 January 1966, the [[37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron]] (37th ARRS) was activated at Da Nang AB operating 5 [[HU-16]]s on loan from the [[31st Rescue Squadron|31st ARRS]] and the [[33d Rescue Squadron|33rd ARRS]], the squadron was responsible for aircrew recovery over North Vietnam, Laos and the Gulf of Tonkin.<ref name=LaPointe>{{cite book|last=LaPointe|first=Robert|title=PJs in Vietnam|publisher=Northern PJ Press|year=2001|isbn=9780970867100|page=175}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Tilford|first=Earl|title=Search and Rescue in Southeast Asia 1961\u20131975|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1980|isbn=9781410222640|page=75}}</ref> In May 1967, Detachment 1 [[38th Rescue Squadron|38th ARRS]] operating [[HH-3]]s at the base was reassigned to the 37th ARRS.<ref name=LaPointe/>{{rp|274}}\n\nIn February 1966, the [[480th Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In July Detachment 3, [[405th Air Expeditionary Wing|405th Fighter Wing]] equipped with F-102s deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nIn April/May 1966, following civil unrest in Da Nang, all USAF personnel were moved from off-base housing into barracks on the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|175}}\n\nIn May 1966, the base supported [[Thanh H\u00f3a Bridge#Operation Carolina Moon|Operation Carolina Moon]] an unsuccessful attempt to destroy the Thanh H\u00f3a Bridge with mines dropped from C-130s.<ref name=Van/>{{rp|258\u20139}}\n\nBy September 1966, the 20th TASS had replaced most of its O-1s with the [[Cessna O-2 Skymaster|O-2A]] with many of these forward deployed to smaller bases close to the [[Vietnamese Demilitarized Zone|DMZ]].<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|242}}\n\nIn October, the [[366th Fighter Wing|366th Tactical Fighter Wing]] deployed to the base from Phan Rang replacing the 35th TFW which moved down to Phan Rang.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} By December 1966 7 F-4 squadrons were operating from the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|160}}\n\nIn March 1967, elements of the [[9th Special Operations Squadron|9th Air Commando Squadron]] equipped with O-2Bs began operating from the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|243}}\n\nDuring the [[Tet Offensive]] attacks in northern [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|I Corps]], many of the detached 20th TASS units returned from their forward bases to the security of Da Nang AB, resulting in longer transit and reduced on-station times for their forward air control missions.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|30\u20131}}\n\nOn 20 September 1969 a USAF F-4 returning from a strike mission collided with an [[Air Vietnam]] [[Douglas C-54 Skymaster|Douglas C-54D-10-DC Skymaster]] (registration XV-NUG) 3&nbsp;kilometers (1.9&nbsp;miles) northwest of the airport, taking off part of the C-54's wing, the C-54 crashed into a plowed field, killing 74 of the 75 people on board and two people working in the field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19690920-1|title=|publisher=Aviation Safety Network|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 1970, the PAVN shelled and rocketed the base killing 1 Airman and one Marine and damaging barracks and communications facilities.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|246}}\n\nBy 1972, with [[Vietnamization]] at an advanced stage, Da Nang AB was one of only 4 major USAF bases remaining in South Vietnam with the 366th TFW based there.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|305}} When the [[Easter Offensive]] began on 30 March 1972 the USAF moved quickly to build up its tactical fighter strength in Vietnam, on 3 April 9 F-4s were deployed to Da Nang AB as part of Operation Commando Fly, these aircraft were soon joined by an additional 9 F-4s and formed the [[35th Fighter Squadron|35th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (35th TFS).<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|338}}\n\nIn late April, a [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52]] made an emergency landing at the base after a hit by an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 missile]] over North Vietnam knocked out 3 of its engines.<ref name=Thompson>{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Wayne|title=To Hanoi and Back The United States Air Force and North Vietnam 1966\u20131973|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2000|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-101001-049.pdf|isbn=978-1410224712|page=227}}</ref>\n\nIn late May, the 366th TFW began moving from Da Nang AB to [[Takhli Royal Thai Air Force Base]], with the personnel of the 390th TFS returning to the US while their aircraft were transferred to other squadrons in Thailand.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|345}} The 35th TFS redeployed to [[Udorn Royal Thai Air Force Base]].<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|345}}\n\n===USMC use===\n[[File:Aerial view of Marine helicopter flight line at Da Nang shortly after SHUFLY's relocation to I Corps in September 1962.jpg|thumb|right|250px|SHUFLY UH-34s of [[HMM-163]] at Da Nang AB in September 1962]]\n[[File:F-4Bs VMFA-115 323 DaNang Jan1966.jpg|thumb|right|250px|F-4Bs of [[VMFA-115]] at Da Nang AB in January 1966]]\n[[File:F-8E Crusader of VMF(AW)-232 taking off from Da Nang c1967.jpg|thumb|right|250px|F-8E of [[VMFA-232|VMF(AW)-232]] taking off from Da Nang AB c.1967]]\nIn early September 1962, [[HMM-163]] codenamed \"SHUFLY\", one of the first [[United States Marine Corps]] (USMC) helicopter units to serve in Vietnam, was redeployed with its support units from [[Marine Aircraft Group 16]] (MABS-16) from [[S\u00f3c Tr\u0103ng Airfield]] to Da Nang Airfield, completing the redeployment by 20 September.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|73\u20134}} HMM-162 was tasked with supporting ARVN operations in I Corps,<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|79}} and conducted their first combat operation deploying units from the ARVN [[2nd Division (South Vietnam)|2nd Division]] on 18 September 1962.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|82}}\n\nThe ARVN, RVNAF, USAF and USMC established a joint [[Air Support Operations Center]] at Da Nang AB to coordinate air support within I Corps.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|80\u20132}} This was later supplemented by an Aviation Headquarters Operations Centre to oversee Army and USMC aviation.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|117}}\n\nOn 11 January 1963, [[HMM-162]] replaced HMM-163 at Da Nang AB and in April a reconnaissance platoon from the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]] was deployed to provide base security.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|111\u20132}} Later in April the US Army's 68th Aviation Company equipped with armed [[Bell UH-1 Iroquois|UH-1Bs]] began operations from the base.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|115}} On 8 June 1963 [[HMM-261]] replaced HMM-162.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|116}} On 2 October [[HMM-361]] replaced HMM-261.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|120}}\n\nOn 1 February 1964, [[HMM-364]] replaced HMM-361 at Da Nang AB, together with its combat support missions HMM-364 was tasked with training VNAF personnel in helicopter operations as it was intended that they would be the last USMC helicopter unit deployed to Vietnam and would depart by 30 June.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|146\u20137}} Following harassment attacks on the Marine compound, on 24 March a platoon from [[1st Battalion 9th Marines]] was deployed to Da Nang AB to increase base security.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|147}} By late May it had become clear that 30 June departure date was unrealistic and so in late June HMM-364 turned over their helicopters to the new VNAF 217th Squadron, HMM-162 returned to Da Nang.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|155\u20136}} On 21 September the USMC evacuated Da Nang AB as [[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Tilda (Basiang)|Typhoon Tilda]] approached, the Marines returned to their damaged base on 23 September.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|159\u201360}} On 29 September 1/9 Marines was replaced by a platoon from Company E [[2nd Battalion 9th Marines]].<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|160\u20131}} In early October HMM-162 was replaced by [[HMM-365]].<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|161}} On 26 November E/2/9 Marines was replaced by the reinforced Company L [[3rd Battalion 9th Marines]].<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|164}}\n\nOn 7 February 1965, following the [[Attack on Camp Holloway]], US President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] ordered [[Operation Flaming Dart|retaliatory airstrikes against North Vietnam]] and the deployment of [[MIM-23 Hawk|HAWK missiles]] to South Vietnam to defend against any attacks by the [[Vietnam People's Air Force]] (VPAF). The USMC [[3rd Low Altitude Air Defense Battalion#Ground Based Air Defense in Vietnam|1st LAAM Battalion]] based on [[Okinawa]] was ordered to deploy to Da Nang. Arriving by C-130 on 8 April, by 9 April the HAWKs were operational at the base.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|4\u20135}}\n\nOn 8 March 1965, in coordination with the amphibious landing of the [[9th Marine Regiment (United States)|9th Marine Regiment]] at [[Red Beach Base Area|Red Beach]] north of Da Nang,<ref name=Kelley>{{cite book|last=Kelley|first=Michael|title=Where we were in Vietnam|publisher=Hellgate Press|year=2002|isbn=978-1555716257|pages=5\u2013439}}</ref> the [[1st Battalion 3rd Marines]] landed at Da Nang AB from [[Naha Air Base]], this marked the first deployment of US combat troops to South Vietnam.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|14}} On 9 March HMM-365 was replaced by HMM-162.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|15}} The [[9th Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|9th Marine Expeditionary Brigade]] (9th MEB) were tasked with defending Da Nang AB, while overall responsibility for defending the Da Nang area remained with the ARVN, SHUFLY was absorbed into [[Marine Aircraft Group 16]] (MAG-16), part of 9th MEB.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|16}}\n\nOn 10 April, [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4Bs]] from [[VMFA-531]] landed at Da Nang AB, this would be the first USMC fighter-bomber squadron deployed to Vietnam.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|25}} On 16 April [[Marine Air Support Squadron 2]] (MASS-2) was deployed to Da Nang AB to provide tactical air control for Marine aviation units and the following day [[VMAQT-1|VMCJ-1]] equipped with [[Douglas F3D Skyknight|EF-10Bs]] deployed to the base. The USMC fixed wing units were designated [[Marine Aircraft Group 11]] (MAG-11).<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|27}}\n\nIn early May 1965, the 9th MEB was redesignated as the [[III Marine Expeditionary Force|3rd Marine Amphibious Force]] (III MAF) and a [[1st Marine Aircraft Wing]] (1st MAW) advanced headquarters was established at Da Nang AB. III MAF and 1st MAW controlled all USMC units in Vietnam which now comprised the enclaves at Da Nang, [[Chu Lai Base Area]] and [[Phu Bai Combat Base]].<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|36}}\n\nOn the early morning of 1 July 1965, the PAVN and Vietcong launched a mortar and sapper attack on the base, destroying one [[Convair F-102 Delta Dagger|F-102]] and two C-130s and damaging a further two F-102s and one C-130.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|56\u20137}}\n\nIn mid-July, [[VMFA-513]] relieved VMFA-531 and [[VMFA-542]] was also deployed to Da Nang AB. On 7 August given the overcrowding at the base, the helicopters of MAG-16 moved to the new [[Marble Mountain Air Facility]], on the Tiensha Peninsula across the Da Nang River from Da Nang AB.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|149}}\n\nOn 15 October, [[VMFA-115]] replaced VMFA-513, on 1 December [[VMFA-323]] replaced VMFA-542 and on 19 December [[VMFA-312|VMF(AW)-312]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|150}} A detachment of four \n[[Lockheed Martin KC-130|KC-130]] tankers from [[VMGR-152]] was also stationed at Da Nang AB to support USMC squadrons.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|157}}\n\nOn 25 January 1966, the Vietcong attacked Da Nang AB with 120mm mortars killing one Marine.<ref name=Shu66>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=An Expanding War, 1966 |publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1982|isbn=9781494285159|page=43}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1966, [[VMFA(AW)-242|VMF (AW)-242]] equipped with [[Grumman A-6 Intruder|A-6As]] was deployed to Da Nang AB.<ref name=Shu66/>{{rp|264\u20135}}\n\nOn 27 February 1967, the PAVN launched a rocket attack hitting the base with more than 50 140mm rockets in one minute, a further rocket attack took place on 15 March.<ref name=Telfer>{{cite book|last=Telfer|first=Gary|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Fighting the North Vietnamese 1967|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1984|isbn=978-1494285449|page=77}}</ref> On 14 July the PAVN launched another rocket attack firing over 50 122mm rockets destroying 10 aircraft, barracks and a bomb dump, damaging a further 40 aircraft and killing 8 Americans and wounding 176.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|108\u20139}}\n\nOn the morning of 3 January 1968, the Vietcong launched more than 50 122mm rockets at the base destroying a Marine F-4B and two USAF aircraft and damaging 17 others.<ref name=Shu68>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: 1968 The Defining Year|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1997|isbn=0160491258|pages=98\u20139}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of 1968, USMC units at Da Nang AB included VMCJ-1, [[VMFA-235|VMF (AW)-235]], VMF (AW)-242 and [[VMFA-122]].<ref name=Shu68/>{{rp|459}} During the [[Tet Offensive]] together with other attacks on US and ARVN facilities in the Da Nang area, on the night of 29 January the Vietcong fired rockets at the base and then at 02:30 on 30 January they launched a sapper and mortar attack on the south of the base killing 4 Marines.<ref name=Shu68/>{{rp|145\u20136}} At 03:30 a renewed rocket attack on the base began with 55 122mm rockets hitting within 20 minutes killing 3 Marines and wounding 11 and destroying 5 aircraft and damaging a further 14.<ref name=Shu68/>{{rp|147\u20138}}\n\nIn January 1969, USMC units at Da Nang AB included VMCJ-1, VMF (AW)-242, [[VMFA-334]] and VMFA-542.<ref name=Smith>{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Charles|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: High Mobility and Standdown 1969|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1988|isbn=978-1494287627|page=220}}</ref> On 23 February 1969 as part of the [[Tet 1969]] attacks, a PAVN rocket attack destroyed a 450,000 gallon fuel tank beside the base and damaged an A-6.<ref name=Smith/>{{rp|97}} On 7 October as part of [[Operation Keystone Cardinal]], a farewell ceremony took place at the base to mark the departure of the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)#Vietnam War|3rd Marine Division]] from South Vietnam.<ref name=Smith/>{{rp|166\u20137}}\n\nAt the beginning of 1970, USMC units at Da Nang AB included VMCJ-1, [[VMFA(AW)-225|VMF (AW)-225]], VMF (AW)-242 and VMFA-542.<ref name=Cosmas>{{cite book|last=Cosmas|first=Graham|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Vietnamization and Redeployment 1970\u20131971|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1988|isbn=978-1482384123|page=270}}</ref> In late January 1970 as part of Operation Keystone Bluejay VMFA-542 departed Vietnam and [[VMO-2]] moved to the base from Marble Mountain Air Facility.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|271}} In July\u2013August as part of Operation Keystone Robin Alpha, VMCJ-1 and VMF (AW)-242 departed Vietnam while the withdrawal of [[Marine Aircraft Group 13]] from [[Chu Lai Air Base]] saw the relocation of VMFA-115 and [[VMA-311]] to Da Nang AB as part of MAG-11.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|271}} During 1970 Marine engineers constructed 170 \"Wonderarch\" concrete and steel aircraft protection shelters at Da Nang AB and Marble Mountain Air Facility.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|326\u20137}}\n\nBeginning in January 1971, as part of Operation Keystone Robin Charlie the 1st MAW headquarters and VMFA-115 departed Da Nang AB for [[MCAS Iwakuni]] while VMO-2 returned to the US, leaving MAG-11 with two squadrons, VMF (AW)-225 and VMA-311 and other assorted assets, by 22 June 1971 all USMC aviation units had left South Vietnam.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|273}}\n\nOn 31 January 1971, 8 PAVN rockets hit the base igniting a 50,000 gallon fuel tank and damaging two KC-130s. On 21 February another rocket attack destroyed a C-130.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|213}}\n\nOn 6 April 1972, USMC squadrons returned to Da Nang AB to confront the PAVN Easter Offensive, with VMFA-115 and VMFA-232 redeploying to the base under the command of [[Marine Aircraft Group 15]] (MAG-15).<ref name=Melson>{{cite book|last=Melson|first=Charles|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: The War That Would Not End, 1971\u20131973|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1991|isbn=978-1482384055|pages=153\u20135}}</ref> On 12 April the base was hit by 122mm rockets killing 14 Vietnamese civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/reports/images.php?img=/images/1683/168300010829.pdf|title=United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam 1972-1973 Command History Volume 1|publisher=United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam|date=15 July 1973|accessdate=25 April 2020|page=44}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> On 14 April [[VMFA-212]] arrived at the base followed the next day by [[H&MS-15]].<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|157}} On 24 April the base was hit by PAVN 122mm rockets prompting a call for Marines to provide base security and on 25 May the 3rd Battalion 9th Marines was deployed to the base.<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|158\u20139}} From 16 June MAG-15 began moving to [[Royal Thai Air Base Nam Phong]], while USMC operations at Da Nang AB were reduced to rearming and refueling.<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|164\u201370}} On 26 January 1973, the date before the [[Paris Peace Accords]] were to come into effect two MAG-15 F-4s were damaged by PAVN rocket fire as they rearmed at Danang AB.<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|216}}\n\n==Capture of Da Nang Air Base by the Vietnamese (1975)==\n{{main|Hue-Da Nang Campaign}}\nOn 11 March 1975, faced with the PAVN invasion and the collapse of the South Vietnamese positions in the Central Highlands, President [[Nguyen Van Thieu]] decided on a new strategy of \"Light at the top, heavy on the bottom\" which essentially involved only defending III Corps and IV Corps, with the ARVN withdrawing from I Corps and II Corps as necessary in the face of PAVN pressure.<ref name=Veith>{{cite book|last=Veith|first=George|title=Black April: The fall of South Vietnam 1973\u201375|publisher=Encounter Books|year=2012|isbn=9781594035722|pages=171\u20132}}</ref> Thieu met with Lieutenant General [[Ng\u00f4 Quang Tr\u01b0\u1edfng]] in Saigon on 13 March and Tr\u01b0\u1edfng understood that he was authorised to concentrate his forces around Da Nang.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|176}} On 19 March Tr\u01b0\u1edfng presented Thieu with alternative plans for the simultaneous withdrawal by road from [[Hu\u1ebf]], [[Chu Lai]] and [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]] to Da Nang or if the road was cut by the PAVN for withdrawal of forces into enclaves at Hu\u1ebf, Chu Lai and Qui Nh\u01a1n and then their evacuation by sea. Thieu agreed that Tr\u01b0\u1edfng should attempt to hold Hu\u1ebf despite misgivings as to the ARVN's ability to hold the city and the navy's ability to supply them.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|286}} Tr\u01b0\u1edfng returned to Da Nang to reorganise his forces for the defense of Hu\u1ebf but was immediately confronted with a PAVN frontal assault against [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province]] and the ARVN soon retreated towards Hu\u1ebf.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|287}} On 21 March the PAVN launched attacks south of Hu\u1ebf aimed at isolating the city and preventing the reinforcement or withdrawal or ARVN forces into the city and establishment of defensive lines.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|291\u20132}} On 22 March Thieu ordered the withdrawal of all ARVN forces between Hu\u1ebf and Da Nang to fall back into an enclave at Da Nang.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|297}}\n\nBy 26 March, Hu\u1ebf and all of [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province|Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb]], [[Th\u1eeba Thi\u00ean Province|Th\u1eeba Thi\u00ean]], [[Qu\u1ea3ng Nam Province|Qu\u1ea3ng Nam]] and [[Qu\u1ea3ng Ng\u00e3i]] Provinces had been captured by the PAVN and Da Nang was isolated.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|323}} General Tr\u01b0\u1edfng organised his remaining forces, which numbered approximately 75,000 troops, into inner and outer defensive lines around the city, meanwhile the PAVN prepared to attack the city from four directions before its defenses could be properly established. Tr\u01b0\u1edfng's defense plans were hampered by the presence of 1\u20131,500,000 refugess and ARVN stragglers who had crowded the city.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|325}} Throughout 26 March evacuation flights by [[Air America (airline)|Air America]], Air Vietnam, the RVNAF and [[World Airways]] from Da Nang AB took place but could not keep up with the vast tide of refugees.<ref name=Boston>{{cite book|last=Dougan|first=Clark|title=The Vietnam Experience: the Fall of the South|publisher=Boston Publishing Company|year=1985|isbn=0939526166|page=77}}</ref> On 27 March the situation at Da Nang AB was becoming increasingly chaotic as panicked refugees surged to board a World Airways flight and began mobbing the other flights and gathering on the taxiways and runways.<ref name=Boston/> By the evening of 27 March all evacuation flights out of the base were stopped, but propeller aircraft continued to evacuate refugees from Marble Mountain Air Facility.<ref name=Boston/>{{rp|77\u20138}} That night General Lanh, Deputy Commander of the RVNAF flew into the base and instructed General Khanh the RVNAF 1st Air Division commander to evacuate all flyable aircraft, 130 aircraft would be evacuated while some 180, including 33 [[Cessna A-37 Dragonfly|A-37s]], were abandoned.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lavalle|first=A|title=USAF Southeast Asia Monograph Series Volume III, The Vietnamese Air Force 1951\u201375|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1985|url=https://media.defense.gov/2010/Oct/13/2001330009/-1/-1/0/AFD-101013-043.pdf|isbn=0912799285|page=76}}</ref>\n\nThe PAVN attack began on the morning of 28 March with an artillery barrage on the city, probing attacks quickly penetrated the ARVN defenses, and the fragile ARVN discipline collapsed and soldiers began to desert their positions and seek refuge for themselves and their families. On the night of 28 March General Tr\u01b0\u1edfng received intelligence that an all-out PAVN assault against the city would commence the next morning and he decided to abandon Da Nang and ordered his forces to move to beaches for evacuation by sea.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|327\u20138}}\n\nOn the morning of 29 March, 2 World Airways [[Boeing 727]]s flew from Saigon to Da Nang to attempt to pick up more refugees. When the first 727 landed at Da Nang AB it was mobbed, 270 people pushed into the plane, all but 3 were ARVN. As the aircraft attempted to take off it was hit by a grenade which jammed the flaps and the main runway was blocked by trucks and the pilot instead took off from a taxiway. A number of ARVN hung onto the undercarriage and in the wheel wells, preventing the retraction of the landing gear, 4 of them survived the flight back to Saigon.<ref name=Boston/>{{rp|81\u20132}}\n\nThe PAVN entered the outskirts of Da Nang by mid-morning on 29 March and by the afternoon were in complete control of the city.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|328}} On 7 April the first VPAF transport aircraft began landing at Da Nang AB to support PAVN operations further south.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|366}} In mid-April the VPAF formed the Quyet Thang (\"Determined to Win\") Squadron at Da Nang AB and began preliminary training of pilots on captured RVNAF A-37s, the squadron would carry out the [[Bombing of Tan Son Nhut Air Base]] on 28 April.<ref>{{cite book|last=Boniface|first=Roger (2008)|title=MiGs over North Vietnam: The Vietnam People's Air Force in Combat, 1965\u201375|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2008|isbn=9780811706964|pages=155\u20136}}</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*On 16 March 1970 a U.S. Navy [[Lockheed EC-121 Warning Star|EC-121 Warning Star]] crashed on landing. The aircraft struck a hangar and caught fire killing 22 of the 31-man crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/reports/images.php?img=/images/1683/168300010812.pdf|title=Headquarters MACV Monthly Summary March 1970|publisher=Headquarters United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam|date=11 July 1970|accessdate=15 March 2020|pages=34-5}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Air Force}}\n*{{Marine Corps}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Da Nang Air Base}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XYavDV00k8Y] Video of Danang Air Base from 1965 to 1970\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0BoHFCwCIIQ] Video of Danang Air Base from 1968\u20139\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Da Nang]]\n[[Category:Installations of the United States Air Force in South Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Military installations closed in 1975]]\n[[Category:Installations of the United States Army in South Vietnam]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the civil use of the facility|Da Nang International Airport}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n|name=Da Nang Air Base\n|ensign=[[File:Vietnam Air Force (south) roundel.svg|60px]]&nbsp;[[File:Roundel of the USAF.svg|60px]] \n|partof=[[Republic of Vietnam Air Force]] (RVNAF)<br>[[Pacific Air Forces]] (USAF)\n|location=\n|coordinates={{Coord|16|02|38|N|108|11|58|E|name=Danang AB|display=inline}}\n|image=\n|caption=\n|map_type = Vietnam\n|map_size = 170\n|map_alt =\n|map_caption = Location of Da Nang Air Base in Vietnam\n|type=Air Force Base\n|code=\n|built=1930s\n|builder=\n|materials=\n|height=\n|used=1930s\u2013Present\n|demolished=\n|condition= Joint Civil/Military Airport\n|ownership=\n|controlledby=\n|garrison=\n|commanders=\n|occupants=\n|battles= [[World War II]]<br>[[First Indochina War]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]\n|events=\n}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| IATA = DAD\n| ICAO = VVDN\n| name = Airfield information\n| elevation-f = 33\n| elevation-m = 10\n| website =\n| r1-number = 17L/35R\n| r1-length-f = 11,483\n| r1-length-m = 3500\n| r1-surface = Asphalt\n| r2-number = 17R/35L\n| r2-length-f = 10,000\n| r2-length-m = 3,048\n| r2-surface = Asphalt\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Da Nang Air Base''' ({{lang-vi|C\u0103n c\u1ee9 kh\u00f4ng qu\u00e2n \u0110\u00e0 N\u1eb5ng}}) (1930s\u20131975) (also known as '''Da Nang Airfield''', '''Tourane Airfield''' or '''Tourane Air Base''') was a [[French Air Force]] and later [[Republic of Vietnam Air Force]] (RVNAF) facility located in the city of [[Da Nang]], [[Vietnam]]. During the [[Vietnam War]] (1959\u20131975), it was a major base with [[United States Army]], [[United States Air Force]] (USAF), and [[United States Marine Corps]] (USMC) units stationed there. [[Air Vietnam]] also used the facility from 1951 to 1975 for civilian domestic and international flights within Southeast Asia.\n\n==Early history==\nOn 22 September 1940, the [[Vichy France|Vichy Government]] signed an agreement with Japan allowing the Japanese to station troops in [[Tonkin]] and use three airfields there.<ref name=Logevall>{{cite book|last=Logevall|first=Fredrik|title=Embers of War: The fall of an Empire and the making of America's Vietnam|publisher=Random House|year=2012|isbn=9780375756474|page=33}}</ref> On 14 July 1941, the Japanese sent the French an ultimatum demanding the use of bases in [[Annam (French protectorate)|Annam]] and [[Cochinchina]], the French acquiesced and by late July, the Japanese occupied [[Cam Ranh Bay]], [[Bien Hoa Air Base]] and Tourane Airfield.<ref name=Logevall/>{{rp|39\u201340}}\n\nIn late 1944, the [[Fourteenth Air Force]] based in southern China began raiding Japanese bases throughout Indochina and on 12 January 1945, the [[United States Third Fleet]] launched attacks on Japanese coastal bases including Da Nang.<ref name=Logevall/>{{rp|68\u20139}}\n\n==Indochina War (1945\u20131954)==\n[[File:Aerial view of Tourane Airfield 01 (Indochina) c1954.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Tourane Airfield in 1954]]\nTourane Airfield was used by the [[French Air Force]] during the [[First Indochina War|French Indochina War]].\n\nIn December 1950, pursuant to the [[Mutual Defense Assistance Act]] and Program, the US delivered [[Douglas A-26 Invader|B-26 Invaders]] to the French and these were used to form the [[Bombardment Group I/19 Gascogne]] based at Tourane.<ref name=Futrell>{{cite book|last=Futrell|first=Robert|title=The United States Air Force in Southeast Asia: The Advisory Years to 1965|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1981|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100525-052.pdf|isbn=9789998843523}}</ref>{{rp|7}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defense.gouv.fr/air/activites/unites-aeriennes/escadrons-de-chasse/escadron-de-chasse-01.091-gascogne|title=Escadron de chasse 01.091 \" Gascogne \"|publisher=French MoD|accessdate=3 May 2016|language=French}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, the US [[Eighteenth Air Force]] [[Fairchild C-119 Flying Boxcar|C-119s]] were deployed to Tourane to support French military operations, a number of these aircraft crewed by civilians later flew in support of French forces in the [[Battle of Dien Bien Phu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.18af.amc.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=19636 |title=18TH AIR FORCE FACT SHEET |publisher=United States Air Force |date=12 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423094112/http://www.18af.amc.af.mil//library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=19636 |archivedate=23 April 2013 }}</ref> In 1953/54 the French laid a NATO-standard {{convert|7800|ft|m|adj=on}} asphalt runway at Tourane.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|52}}\n\nIn January 1954, the USAF delivered a further 16 B-26s and 3 RB-26s to Tourane and in February assigned USAF maintenance and supply personnel to Tourane on temporary duty to support B-26 operations.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|17}} On 19 March the USAF deployed the 1808th Airways and Air Communications Service Squadron to Indochina with 60 enlisted men and one civilian at Tourane.<ref name=Williams>{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Kenneth|title=The US Air Force in Southeast Asia and the Vietnam War A Narrative Chronology Volume I: The Early Years through 1959|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2019|url=https://media.defense.gov/2019/Feb/22/2002092352/-1/-1/1/USAF%20Vietnam%20Chronology%20v1.pdf|isbn=}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|117}} On 6 April the USAF delivered 11 B\u201326s to Tourane  for loan to the French.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|130}} The USAF delivered 18 [[Douglas C-47 Skytrain|C-47s]] to Tourane on 9 April to replace aircraft losses.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|24}} Later in April [[VMA-324]] delivered 25 [[Vought F4U Corsair|F4U/G Corsairs]] to the French Air Force at Tourane.<ref name=Whitlow>{{cite book|last=Whitlow|first=Robert|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam:The Advisory And Combat Assistance Era, 1954\u20131964|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1977|isbn=1494285290|page=71}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the French defeat at Dien Bien Phu and in anticipation of the [[Geneva Conference (1954)|Indochina peace treaty]], on 23 May the USAF C-119 detachment at [[Cat Bi International Airport#First Indochina War|Cat Bi Air Base]] moved to Tourane.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|149}}\n\nOn 14 June 1954 [[Viet Minh]] troops captured five USAF airmen of the [[315th Air Division]] stationed at Tourane while they were on an unauthorized beach outing. They were held at a small camp about {{convert|60|mi}} south of Tourane that was ringed by mines and pits with bamboo stakes. The airmen remained in captivity until 31 August when they were released to the French as part of a prisoner exchange.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|156}}\n\nOn 19 July 1954 the USAF 6424th Air Depot Wing detachment that had supported French B\u201326 operations at Tourane completed its closeout and was inactivated.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|165}}\n\nOn 6 September the last of the B-26s and C-119s on loan to the French departed from Tourane.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|31}}\n\n==Republic of Vietnam Air Force use (1955\u20131970)==\n[[File:VNAF Skyraider at Da Nang 1967.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Republic of Vietnam Air Force|RVNAF]] [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|A-1]] at Da Nang AB in 1967]]\nBy the end of the Indochina War, the French had established a small Republic of Vietnam Air Force (RVNAF) consisting of 2 squadrons of [[Fieseler Fi 156#French production|Morane-Saulnier MS.500]] and one of [[Morane-Saulnier MS.315]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|36}} In January 1955, [[Military Assistance Advisory Group|MAAG Vietnam]] decided that the RVNAF would comprise one fighter, two liaison and two transport squadrons and that training would be undertaken by the French. Under the Mutual Defence Assistance Program, the US delivered 28 [[Grumman F8F Bearcat|F8Fs]], 35 C-47s and 60 [[O-1 Bird Dog|L-19s]] to the RVNAF to equip the planned expansion.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|49\u201350}} On 19 September 1955 the French turned over Tourane Airfield to the RVNAF, at the time the base had a {{convert|7850|ft}} runway, with potential extension of at least {{convert|1000|ft}}.<ref name=Williams/>{{rp|208\u20139}} On 1 June 1957 all RVNAF training responsibility passed from the French to the United States.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|50}}\n\nIn November 1955, the RVNAF 1st Liaison Squadron moved to Da Nang AB from [[Hu\u1ebf]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|272}}\n\nIn October 1961, the 2nd Helicopter Squadron was activated at Da Nang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|273}}\n\nIn December 1961 the 3rd Liaison Squadron was activated at Da Nang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|273}}\n\nIn mid-1962, the RVNAF 2nd Fighter Squadron equipped with [[North American T-28 Trojan|T-28s]] became operational at [[Nha Trang Air Base]] and began detaching 6 aircraft to Da Nang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|132}}\n\nIn January 1963, the 2nd Helicopter Squadron was redesignated the 213th Helicopter Squadron, the 1st Liaison Squadron was redesignated the 110th Liaison Squadron and the 3rd Liaison Squadron was redesignated the 114th Liaison Squadron.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|273}}\n\nIn February 1964, the 516th Fighter Squadron equipped with 15 [[Douglas A-1 Skyraider|A-1 Skyraiders]] moved to Da Nang AB from Nha Trang AB.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|274}} On 15 March 1964 the RVNAF established a Tactical Wing Headquarters at the base.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|211}} In May the 217th Helicopter Squadron was established at the base.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|274}}\n\nOn 8 February 1965, RVNAF commander [[Nguy\u1ec5n Cao K\u1ef3]] led VNAF A-1s from the base on a [[Operation Flaming Dart|retaliatory raid against North Vietnamese targets]].<ref name=Schlight>{{cite book|last=Schlight|first=John|title=The United States Air Force in Southeast Asia: The War in South Vietnam The Years of the Offensive 1965\u20131968|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1999|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-101013-038.pdf|isbn=9780912799513|page=60}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March 1965, 20 A-1s from the base participated in the first attacks of [[Operation Rolling Thunder]], striking the [[Vietnam People's Navy]] base at [[Qu\u1ea3ng Kh\u00ea]].<ref name=Van>{{cite book|last=Van Staaveren|first=Jacob|title=Gradual Failure: The Air War over North Vietnam 1965\u20131966|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2002|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100526-034.pdf|isbn=9781508779094|page=84}}</ref> On 14 March the VNAF led by General K\u1ef3 participated in attacks on barracks on H\u00f2n Gi\u00f3 island.<ref name=Van/>{{rp|85}}\n\nIn August 1965, 4 USAF [[Martin B-57 Canberra|B-57Bs]] operating from the base were nominally transferred to the RVNAF becoming their first jet aircraft.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|88}}\n\nIn 1970, the RVNAF units at Da Nang AB were reorganized as the First Air Division with responsibility for [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|Military Region I]].<ref name=Nalty>{{cite book|last=Nalty|first=Bernard|title=The United States Air Force in Southeast Asia: The War in South Vietnam Air War over South Vietnam 1968\u20131975|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2000|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-100924-004.pdf|isbn=9781478118640|page=213}}</ref> Also during that year the RVNAF began building family housing at the base for its personnel.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|214}}\n\n==United States military use (1962\u20131972)==\nDa Nang Air Base was used as a primary entry point for American service members flying into Vietnam fighting in the Vietnam War. It was used by the United States Marine Corps (USMC) as well as the US Air force (USAF).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hoffman |first1=David |title=Interview - Bill Ehrhart (Making sense of the sixties) |url=https://ew.com/article/1991/01/18/making-sense-sixties/ |website=www.wdehrhart.com |publisher=Hoffman and Ehrhart |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===US Army use===\nFrom January 1962 until September the [[93rd Transportation Company (Light Helicopter)]] with [[Piasecki H-21|Piasecki CH-21C Shawnee's]] was based here.<ref name=Dunstan>{{cite book|last=Dunstan|first=S|title=Vietnam Choppers|year=1988|publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd|isbn=0-85045-572-3}}</ref>{{rp|20}} During February the company was joined by the [[339th Transportation Company (Direct Support)]]. In September 1962, the CH-21's left and were replaced by [[VMM-362|HMM-362]] with the [[611th Transportation Company (Aircraft Direct Support)]].<ref name=Dunstan/>{{rp|21}}\n\n===USAF use===\n[[File:F-100Ds 416TFS DaNang 1965.jpg|thumb|right|250px|F-100Ds of the [[416th Fighter Squadron]] at Da Nang AB in 1965]]\n[[File:64th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron Convair F-102A-75-CO Delta Dagger 56-1333 Da Nang 1966.jpg|thumb|right|250px|64th FIS F-102A landing at Da Nang AB, 1966]]\n[[File:Danang Air Field, September 1966 (17087464072).jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[Northwest Airlines]] [[Boeing 707]] at Da Nang AB in September 1966]]\n[[File:Da Nang Air Base during the Vietnam War.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Da Nang AB in the late 1960s]]\n[[File:37th ARRSq Revetments, DaNang, RVN 1970-71.jpg|thumb|right|250px|[[37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron|37th ARRS]] [[Sikorsky MH-53|HH-53s]] at Da Nang AB c.1970]]\nIn January 1962, the USAF [[5th Tactical Control Group]] was deployed to Da Nang AB to provide air support operations in [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|I Corps]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|106}} By 2 March [[Fairchild C-123 Provider|C-123s]] were stationed at the base under [[Project Mule Train]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|108}} On 20 May 1962 the 6222nd Air Base Squadron was formed at the base to support VNAF operations and the growing USAF presence through [[Farm Gate (military operation)|Farm Gate]] operations.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|101}}\n\nOn 15 June 1962, 12 C-123s from the [[777th Expeditionary Airlift Squadron|777th Troop Carrier Squadron]] deployed to the base forming the Tactical Air Force Transport Squadron Provisional-2 to supplement the existing Mule Train operations and those of the US Army's 18th Fixed Wing Aviation Company equipped with [[de Havilland Canada DHC-3 Otter|U-1 Otters]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|110\u20131}}\n\nIn early 1962, the base runway was asphalt covered and {{convert|7900|ft|m|adj=on}} long while the taxiways and parking areas were covered in [[Marston Mat|Pierced steel planking]] (PSP).<ref name=Tregaskis>{{cite book|last=Tregaskis|first=Richard|title=Southeast Asia:Building the Bases, The History of Construction in Southeast Asia|publisher=U.S. Navy Seabee Museum|year=1975|url=https://www.history.navy.mil/content/dam/museums/Seabee/Online%20Reading%20Room/Manuals%20and%20Publications/Publications/Southeast%20Asia%2C%20Building%20The%20Bases%2C%20A%20History%20Of%20Const.pdf|isbn=9781461097235|page=42}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1963, the 777th Troop Carrier Squadron equipped with 16 C-123s was transferred to the base and later that year the base's existing Mule Train operations were redesignated as the [[311th Troop Carrier Squadron]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|167\u201371}}\n\nIn early 1964, the [[U.S. Navy]] [[Officer in Charge of Construction RVN]] (OICC) directed the American construction contractor [[RMK-BRJ]] to rebuild and extend the existing runway to 10,000 feet long (3,050 meters), with new asphalt paving. This was completed in July 1964.<ref name=Tregaskis/>{{rp|66}}\n\nOn 5 August 1964, following the [[Gulf of Tonkin incident]], 6 [[Convair F-102 Delta Dagger|F-102s]] from the [[509th Tactical Fighter Squadron|509th Fighter Squadron]] and 8 [[North American F-100 Super Sabre|F-100s]] from the [[615th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (615th TFS) deployed to Da Nang AB from [[Clark Air Base]] in the Philippines.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|229}} The F-100s were proposed to be used for a strike against the [[Vietnam People's Air Force]] (VPAF) [[Ph\u00fac Y\u00ean Air Base]] as part of the US response to the incident, however approval for the strike was denied.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|230\u20132}}\n\nCommencing in December 1964, Da Nang AB was used to support [[Operation Barrel Roll]], the covert air war in neighbouring Laos. On 14 December [[Republic F-105 Thunderchief|F-105s]] from the [[80th Fighter Squadron|80th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] based at [[Korat Royal Thai Air Force Base]], Thailand staged through Da Nang for the initial strikes supported by the base's F-100s. Later that month F-105s from the [[44th Fighter Squadron|44th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base for further strikes near [[Tchepone]],<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|256\u20137}} these aircraft would form Detachment 2 [[18th Wing|18th Tactical Fighter Wing]].<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|256\u20137}} Also in December the [[613th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nIn February 1965, 12 F-100s from the [[3d Wing|3rd Tactical Fighter Wing]] deployed to the base to support the [[Operation Flaming Dart]] airstrikes.<ref name=Futrell/>{{rp|274}}\n\nOn 2 March 1965, F-100s, F-105s and VNAF A-1s from the base participated in the first attacks of Operation Rolling Thunder, striking the naval base at Qu\u1ea3ng Kh\u00ea, losing 2 F-100s in the attack.<ref name=Van/>\n\nBy March 1965, with the base overcrowded by the arrival of new squadrons, a major expansion was approved. In August 1965, the OICC directed RMK-BRJ to construct a second  {{convert|10000|ft|m|adj=on}} parallel runway and paved taxiways and parking areas.<ref name=Tregaskis/>{{rp|149\u2013150}}<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|26\u20138}} The second runway opened in July 1966.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|158}}\n\nIn March 1965, the [[35th Fighter Wing|35th Tactical Fighter Wing]] (35th TFW) deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}In April the [[615th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/> The [[416th Fighter Squadron|416th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base before moving to [[Bien Hoa Air Base]] in mid-May.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} Also in April the [[476th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (476th TFS) equipped with [[Lockheed F-104 Starfighter|F-104Cs]] was deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In May the [[20th Tactical Air Support Squadron]] (20th TASS) equipped with [[Cessna O-1 Bird Dog|O-1s]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In June the 615th TFS returned to the US.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|55}} In mid-June the [[8th Special Operations Squadron|8th Bombardment Squadron]] equipped with [[Martin B-57 Canberra|B-57Bs]] moved to the base from Bien Hoa, these would be rotated with other B-57s from the [[13th Bomb Squadron|13th Bombardment Squadron]] until September 1966 when they would be moved to [[Phan Rang Air Base]].<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nOn the early morning of 1 July 1965, the PAVN and Vietcong launched a mortar and sapper attack on the base, destroying one F-102 and two [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130s]] and damaging a further two F-102s and one C-130.<ref name=Shu65>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=The Landing and the Buildup, 1965 |publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1978|isbn=1494287552|pages=56\u20137}}</ref>\n\nIn July, the [[436th Tactical Fighter Training Squadron|436th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (436th TFS) replaced the 476th TFS.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In October the [[435th Fighter Training Squadron|435th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] replaced the 436th TFS.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In November the [[390th Electronic Combat Squadron|390th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (390th TFS) equipped with [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4s]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nOn 1 January 1966, the 4503rd Tactical Fighter Squadron equipped with the [[Northrop F-5|F-5A ''Skoshi Tiger'']] moved to the base for trial operations over North Vietnam and Laos.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|89\u201390}} The F-5s returned to Bien Hoa in early February and returned to Da Nang AB from 20 February to 10 March when they returned again to Bien Hoa and were redesignated as the 10th Fighter Squadron.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|125}}\n\nOn 8 January 1966, the [[37th Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Squadron]] (37th ARRS) was activated at Da Nang AB operating 5 [[HU-16]]s on loan from the [[31st Rescue Squadron|31st ARRS]] and the [[33d Rescue Squadron|33rd ARRS]], the squadron was responsible for aircrew recovery over North Vietnam, Laos and the Gulf of Tonkin.<ref name=LaPointe>{{cite book|last=LaPointe|first=Robert|title=PJs in Vietnam|publisher=Northern PJ Press|year=2001|isbn=9780970867100|page=175}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Tilford|first=Earl|title=Search and Rescue in Southeast Asia 1961\u20131975|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1980|isbn=9781410222640|page=75}}</ref> In May 1967, Detachment 1 [[38th Rescue Squadron|38th ARRS]] operating [[HH-3]]s at the base was reassigned to the 37th ARRS.<ref name=LaPointe/>{{rp|274}}\n\nIn February 1966, the [[480th Fighter Squadron]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} In July Detachment 3, [[405th Air Expeditionary Wing|405th Fighter Wing]] equipped with F-102s deployed to the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}}\n\nIn April/May 1966, following civil unrest in Da Nang, all USAF personnel were moved from off-base housing into barracks on the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|175}}\n\nIn May 1966, the base supported [[Thanh H\u00f3a Bridge#Operation Carolina Moon|Operation Carolina Moon]] an unsuccessful attempt to destroy the Thanh H\u00f3a Bridge with mines dropped from C-130s.<ref name=Van/>{{rp|258\u20139}}\n\nBy September 1966, the 20th TASS had replaced most of its O-1s with the [[Cessna O-2 Skymaster|O-2A]] with many of these forward deployed to smaller bases close to the [[Vietnamese Demilitarized Zone|DMZ]].<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|242}}\n\nIn October, the [[366th Fighter Wing|366th Tactical Fighter Wing]] deployed to the base from Phan Rang replacing the 35th TFW which moved down to Phan Rang.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|Appendix 1}} By December 1966 7 F-4 squadrons were operating from the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|160}}\n\nIn March 1967, elements of the [[9th Special Operations Squadron|9th Air Commando Squadron]] equipped with O-2Bs began operating from the base.<ref name=Schlight/>{{rp|243}}\n\nDuring the [[Tet Offensive]] attacks in northern [[I Corps (South Vietnam)|I Corps]], many of the detached 20th TASS units returned from their forward bases to the security of Da Nang AB, resulting in longer transit and reduced on-station times for their forward air control missions.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|30\u20131}}\n\nOn 20 September 1969 a USAF F-4 returning from a strike mission collided with an [[Air Vietnam]] [[Douglas C-54 Skymaster|Douglas C-54D-10-DC Skymaster]] (registration XV-NUG) 3&nbsp;kilometers (1.9&nbsp;miles) northwest of the airport, taking off part of the C-54's wing, the C-54 crashed into a plowed field, killing 74 of the 75 people on board and two people working in the field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19690920-1|title=|publisher=Aviation Safety Network|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 1970, the PAVN shelled and rocketed the base killing 1 Airman and one Marine and damaging barracks and communications facilities.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|246}}\n\nBy 1972, with [[Vietnamization]] at an advanced stage, Da Nang AB was one of only 4 major USAF bases remaining in South Vietnam with the 366th TFW based there.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|305}} When the [[Easter Offensive]] began on 30 March 1972 the USAF moved quickly to build up its tactical fighter strength in Vietnam, on 3 April 9 F-4s were deployed to Da Nang AB as part of Operation Commando Fly, these aircraft were soon joined by an additional 9 F-4s and formed the [[35th Fighter Squadron|35th Tactical Fighter Squadron]] (35th TFS).<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|338}}\n\nIn late April, a [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52]] made an emergency landing at the base after a hit by an [[S-75 Dvina|SA-2 missile]] over North Vietnam knocked out 3 of its engines.<ref name=Thompson>{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Wayne|title=To Hanoi and Back The United States Air Force and North Vietnam 1966\u20131973|publisher=Air Force History and Museums Program|year=2000|url=http://www.afhso.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-101001-049.pdf|isbn=978-1410224712|page=227}}</ref>\n\nIn late May, the 366th TFW began moving from Da Nang AB to [[Takhli Royal Thai Air Force Base]], with the personnel of the 390th TFS returning to the US while their aircraft were transferred to other squadrons in Thailand.<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|345}} The 35th TFS redeployed to [[Udorn Royal Thai Air Force Base]].<ref name=Nalty/>{{rp|345}}\n\n===USMC use===\n[[File:Aerial view of Marine helicopter flight line at Da Nang shortly after SHUFLY's relocation to I Corps in September 1962.jpg|thumb|right|250px|SHUFLY UH-34s of [[HMM-163]] at Da Nang AB in September 1962]]\n[[File:F-4Bs VMFA-115 323 DaNang Jan1966.jpg|thumb|right|250px|F-4Bs of [[VMFA-115]] at Da Nang AB in January 1966]]\n[[File:F-8E Crusader of VMF(AW)-232 taking off from Da Nang c1967.jpg|thumb|right|250px|F-8E of [[VMFA-232|VMF(AW)-232]] taking off from Da Nang AB c.1967]]\nIn early September 1962, [[HMM-163]] codenamed \"SHUFLY\", one of the first [[United States Marine Corps]] (USMC) helicopter units to serve in Vietnam, was redeployed with its support units from [[Marine Aircraft Group 16]] (MABS-16) from [[S\u00f3c Tr\u0103ng Airfield]] to Da Nang Airfield, completing the redeployment by 20 September.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|73\u20134}} HMM-162 was tasked with supporting ARVN operations in I Corps,<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|79}} and conducted their first combat operation deploying units from the ARVN [[2nd Division (South Vietnam)|2nd Division]] on 18 September 1962.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|82}}\n\nThe ARVN, RVNAF, USAF and USMC established a joint [[Air Support Operations Center]] at Da Nang AB to coordinate air support within I Corps.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|80\u20132}} This was later supplemented by an Aviation Headquarters Operations Centre to oversee Army and USMC aviation.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|117}}\n\nOn 11 January 1963, [[HMM-162]] replaced HMM-163 at Da Nang AB and in April a reconnaissance platoon from the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)|3rd Marine Division]] was deployed to provide base security.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|111\u20132}} Later in April the US Army's 68th Aviation Company equipped with armed [[Bell UH-1 Iroquois|UH-1Bs]] began operations from the base.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|115}} On 8 June 1963 [[HMM-261]] replaced HMM-162.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|116}} On 2 October [[HMM-361]] replaced HMM-261.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|120}}\n\nOn 1 February 1964, [[HMM-364]] replaced HMM-361 at Da Nang AB, together with its combat support missions HMM-364 was tasked with training VNAF personnel in helicopter operations as it was intended that they would be the last USMC helicopter unit deployed to Vietnam and would depart by 30 June.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|146\u20137}} Following harassment attacks on the Marine compound, on 24 March a platoon from [[1st Battalion 9th Marines]] was deployed to Da Nang AB to increase base security.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|147}} By late May it had become clear that 30 June departure date was unrealistic and so in late June HMM-364 turned over their helicopters to the new VNAF 217th Squadron, HMM-162 returned to Da Nang.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|155\u20136}} On 21 September the USMC evacuated Da Nang AB as [[1964 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Tilda (Basiang)|Typhoon Tilda]] approached, the Marines returned to their damaged base on 23 September.<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|159\u201360}} On 29 September 1/9 Marines was replaced by a platoon from Company E [[2nd Battalion 9th Marines]].<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|160\u20131}} In early October HMM-162 was replaced by [[HMM-365]].<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|161}} On 26 November E/2/9 Marines was replaced by the reinforced Company L [[3rd Battalion 9th Marines]].<ref name=Whitlow/>{{rp|164}}\n\nOn 7 February 1965, following the [[Attack on Camp Holloway]], US President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] ordered [[Operation Flaming Dart|retaliatory airstrikes against North Vietnam]] and the deployment of [[MIM-23 Hawk|HAWK missiles]] to South Vietnam to defend against any attacks by the [[Vietnam People's Air Force]] (VPAF). The USMC [[3rd Low Altitude Air Defense Battalion#Ground Based Air Defense in Vietnam|1st LAAM Battalion]] based on [[Okinawa]] was ordered to deploy to Da Nang. Arriving by C-130 on 8 April, by 9 April the HAWKs were operational at the base.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|4\u20135}}\n\nOn 8 March 1965, in coordination with the amphibious landing of the [[9th Marine Regiment (United States)|9th Marine Regiment]] at [[Red Beach Base Area|Red Beach]] north of Da Nang,<ref name=Kelley>{{cite book|last=Kelley|first=Michael|title=Where we were in Vietnam|publisher=Hellgate Press|year=2002|isbn=978-1555716257|pages=5\u2013439}}</ref> the [[1st Battalion 3rd Marines]] landed at Da Nang AB from [[Naha Air Base]], this marked the first deployment of US combat troops to South Vietnam.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|14}} On 9 March HMM-365 was replaced by HMM-162.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|15}} The [[9th Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|9th Marine Expeditionary Brigade]] (9th MEB) were tasked with defending Da Nang AB, while overall responsibility for defending the Da Nang area remained with the ARVN, SHUFLY was absorbed into [[Marine Aircraft Group 16]] (MAG-16), part of 9th MEB.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|16}}\n\nOn 10 April, [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4Bs]] from [[VMFA-531]] landed at Da Nang AB, this would be the first USMC fighter-bomber squadron deployed to Vietnam.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|25}} On 16 April [[Marine Air Support Squadron 2]] (MASS-2) was deployed to Da Nang AB to provide tactical air control for Marine aviation units and the following day [[VMAQT-1|VMCJ-1]] equipped with [[Douglas F3D Skyknight|EF-10Bs]] deployed to the base. The USMC fixed wing units were designated [[Marine Aircraft Group 11]] (MAG-11).<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|27}}\n\nIn early May 1965, the 9th MEB was redesignated as the [[III Marine Expeditionary Force|3rd Marine Amphibious Force]] (III MAF) and a [[1st Marine Aircraft Wing]] (1st MAW) advanced headquarters was established at Da Nang AB. III MAF and 1st MAW controlled all USMC units in Vietnam which now comprised the enclaves at Da Nang, [[Chu Lai Base Area]] and [[Phu Bai Combat Base]].<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|36}}\n\nOn the early morning of 1 July 1965, the PAVN and Vietcong launched a mortar and sapper attack on the base, destroying one [[Convair F-102 Delta Dagger|F-102]] and two C-130s and damaging a further two F-102s and one C-130.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|56\u20137}}\n\nIn mid-July, [[VMFA-513]] relieved VMFA-531 and [[VMFA-542]] was also deployed to Da Nang AB. On 7 August given the overcrowding at the base, the helicopters of MAG-16 moved to the new [[Marble Mountain Air Facility]], on the Tiensha Peninsula across the Da Nang River from Da Nang AB.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|149}}\n\nOn 15 October, [[VMFA-115]] replaced VMFA-513, on 1 December [[VMFA-323]] replaced VMFA-542 and on 19 December [[VMFA-312|VMF(AW)-312]] deployed to the base.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|150}} A detachment of four \n[[Lockheed Martin KC-130|KC-130]] tankers from [[VMGR-152]] was also stationed at Da Nang AB to support USMC squadrons.<ref name=Shu65/>{{rp|157}}\n\nOn 25 January 1966, the Vietcong attacked Da Nang AB with 120mm mortars killing one Marine.<ref name=Shu66>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=An Expanding War, 1966 |publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1982|isbn=9781494285159|page=43}}</ref>\n\nIn late 1966, [[VMFA(AW)-242|VMF (AW)-242]] equipped with [[Grumman A-6 Intruder|A-6As]] was deployed to Da Nang AB.<ref name=Shu66/>{{rp|264\u20135}}\n\nOn 27 February 1967, the PAVN launched a rocket attack hitting the base with more than 50 140mm rockets in one minute, a further rocket attack took place on 15 March.<ref name=Telfer>{{cite book|last=Telfer|first=Gary|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Fighting the North Vietnamese 1967|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1984|isbn=978-1494285449|page=77}}</ref> On 14 July the PAVN launched another rocket attack firing over 50 122mm rockets destroying 10 aircraft, barracks and a bomb dump, damaging a further 40 aircraft and killing 8 Americans and wounding 176.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|108\u20139}}\n\nOn the morning of 3 January 1968, the Vietcong launched more than 50 122mm rockets at the base destroying a Marine F-4B and two USAF aircraft and damaging 17 others.<ref name=Shu68>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: 1968 The Defining Year|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1997|isbn=0160491258|pages=98\u20139}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of 1968, USMC units at Da Nang AB included VMCJ-1, [[VMFA-235|VMF (AW)-235]], VMF (AW)-242 and [[VMFA-122]].<ref name=Shu68/>{{rp|459}} During the [[Tet Offensive]] together with other attacks on US and ARVN facilities in the Da Nang area, on the night of 29 January the Vietcong fired rockets at the base and then at 02:30 on 30 January they launched a sapper and mortar attack on the south of the base killing 4 Marines.<ref name=Shu68/>{{rp|145\u20136}} At 03:30 a renewed rocket attack on the base began with 55 122mm rockets hitting within 20 minutes killing 3 Marines and wounding 11 and destroying 5 aircraft and damaging a further 14.<ref name=Shu68/>{{rp|147\u20138}}\n\nIn January 1969, USMC units at Da Nang AB included VMCJ-1, VMF (AW)-242, [[VMFA-334]] and VMFA-542.<ref name=Smith>{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Charles|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: High Mobility and Standdown 1969|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1988|isbn=978-1494287627|page=220}}</ref> On 23 February 1969 as part of the [[Tet 1969]] attacks, a PAVN rocket attack destroyed a 450,000 gallon fuel tank beside the base and damaged an A-6.<ref name=Smith/>{{rp|97}} On 7 October as part of [[Operation Keystone Cardinal]], a farewell ceremony took place at the base to mark the departure of the [[3rd Marine Division (United States)#Vietnam War|3rd Marine Division]] from South Vietnam.<ref name=Smith/>{{rp|166\u20137}}\n\nAt the beginning of 1970, USMC units at Da Nang AB included VMCJ-1, [[VMFA(AW)-225|VMF (AW)-225]], VMF (AW)-242 and VMFA-542.<ref name=Cosmas>{{cite book|last=Cosmas|first=Graham|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Vietnamization and Redeployment 1970\u20131971|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1988|isbn=978-1482384123|page=270}}</ref> In late January 1970 as part of Operation Keystone Bluejay VMFA-542 departed Vietnam and [[VMO-2]] moved to the base from Marble Mountain Air Facility.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|271}} In July\u2013August as part of Operation Keystone Robin Alpha, VMCJ-1 and VMF (AW)-242 departed Vietnam while the withdrawal of [[Marine Aircraft Group 13]] from [[Chu Lai Air Base]] saw the relocation of VMFA-115 and [[VMA-311]] to Da Nang AB as part of MAG-11.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|271}} During 1970 Marine engineers constructed 170 \"Wonderarch\" concrete and steel aircraft protection shelters at Da Nang AB and Marble Mountain Air Facility.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|326\u20137}}\n\nBeginning in January 1971, as part of Operation Keystone Robin Charlie the 1st MAW headquarters and VMFA-115 departed Da Nang AB for [[MCAS Iwakuni]] while VMO-2 returned to the US, leaving MAG-11 with two squadrons, VMF (AW)-225 and VMA-311 and other assorted assets, by 22 June 1971 all USMC aviation units had left South Vietnam.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|273}}\n\nOn 31 January 1971, 8 PAVN rockets hit the base igniting a 50,000 gallon fuel tank and damaging two KC-130s. On 21 February another rocket attack destroyed a C-130.<ref name=Cosmas/>{{rp|213}}\n\nOn 6 April 1972, USMC squadrons returned to Da Nang AB to confront the PAVN Easter Offensive, with VMFA-115 and VMFA-232 redeploying to the base under the command of [[Marine Aircraft Group 15]] (MAG-15).<ref name=Melson>{{cite book|last=Melson|first=Charles|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: The War That Would Not End, 1971\u20131973|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1991|isbn=978-1482384055|pages=153\u20135}}</ref> On 12 April the base was hit by 122mm rockets killing 14 Vietnamese civilians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/reports/images.php?img=/images/1683/168300010829.pdf|title=1972-1973 Command History Volume 1|publisher=United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam|date=15 July 1973|accessdate=25 April 2020|page=44}}{{PD-notice}}</ref> On 14 April [[VMFA-212]] arrived at the base followed the next day by [[H&MS-15]].<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|157}} On 24 April the base was hit by PAVN 122mm rockets prompting a call for Marines to provide base security and on 25 May the 3rd Battalion 9th Marines was deployed to the base.<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|158\u20139}} From 16 June MAG-15 began moving to [[Royal Thai Air Base Nam Phong]], while USMC operations at Da Nang AB were reduced to rearming and refueling.<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|164\u201370}} On 26 January 1973, the date before the [[Paris Peace Accords]] were to come into effect two MAG-15 F-4s were damaged by PAVN rocket fire as they rearmed at Danang AB.<ref name=Melson/>{{rp|216}}\n\n==Capture of Da Nang Air Base by the Vietnamese (1975)==\n{{main|Hue-Da Nang Campaign}}\nOn 11 March 1975, faced with the PAVN invasion and the collapse of the South Vietnamese positions in the Central Highlands, President [[Nguyen Van Thieu]] decided on a new strategy of \"Light at the top, heavy on the bottom\" which essentially involved only defending III Corps and IV Corps, with the ARVN withdrawing from I Corps and II Corps as necessary in the face of PAVN pressure.<ref name=Veith>{{cite book|last=Veith|first=George|title=Black April: The fall of South Vietnam 1973\u201375|publisher=Encounter Books|year=2012|isbn=9781594035722|pages=171\u20132}}</ref> Thieu met with Lieutenant General [[Ng\u00f4 Quang Tr\u01b0\u1edfng]] in Saigon on 13 March and Tr\u01b0\u1edfng understood that he was authorised to concentrate his forces around Da Nang.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|176}} On 19 March Tr\u01b0\u1edfng presented Thieu with alternative plans for the simultaneous withdrawal by road from [[Hu\u1ebf]], [[Chu Lai]] and [[Qui Nh\u01a1n]] to Da Nang or if the road was cut by the PAVN for withdrawal of forces into enclaves at Hu\u1ebf, Chu Lai and Qui Nh\u01a1n and then their evacuation by sea. Thieu agreed that Tr\u01b0\u1edfng should attempt to hold Hu\u1ebf despite misgivings as to the ARVN's ability to hold the city and the navy's ability to supply them.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|286}} Tr\u01b0\u1edfng returned to Da Nang to reorganise his forces for the defense of Hu\u1ebf but was immediately confronted with a PAVN frontal assault against [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province]] and the ARVN soon retreated towards Hu\u1ebf.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|287}} On 21 March the PAVN launched attacks south of Hu\u1ebf aimed at isolating the city and preventing the reinforcement or withdrawal or ARVN forces into the city and establishment of defensive lines.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|291\u20132}} On 22 March Thieu ordered the withdrawal of all ARVN forces between Hu\u1ebf and Da Nang to fall back into an enclave at Da Nang.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|297}}\n\nBy 26 March, Hu\u1ebf and all of [[Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb Province|Qu\u1ea3ng Tr\u1ecb]], [[Th\u1eeba Thi\u00ean Province|Th\u1eeba Thi\u00ean]], [[Qu\u1ea3ng Nam Province|Qu\u1ea3ng Nam]] and [[Qu\u1ea3ng Ng\u00e3i]] Provinces had been captured by the PAVN and Da Nang was isolated.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|323}} General Tr\u01b0\u1edfng organised his remaining forces, which numbered approximately 75,000 troops, into inner and outer defensive lines around the city, meanwhile the PAVN prepared to attack the city from four directions before its defenses could be properly established. Tr\u01b0\u1edfng's defense plans were hampered by the presence of 1\u20131,500,000 refugess and ARVN stragglers who had crowded the city.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|325}} Throughout 26 March evacuation flights by [[Air America (airline)|Air America]], Air Vietnam, the RVNAF and [[World Airways]] from Da Nang AB took place but could not keep up with the vast tide of refugees.<ref name=Boston>{{cite book|last=Dougan|first=Clark|title=The Vietnam Experience: the Fall of the South|publisher=Boston Publishing Company|year=1985|isbn=0939526166|page=77}}</ref> On 27 March the situation at Da Nang AB was becoming increasingly chaotic as panicked refugees surged to board a World Airways flight and began mobbing the other flights and gathering on the taxiways and runways.<ref name=Boston/> By the evening of 27 March all evacuation flights out of the base were stopped, but propeller aircraft continued to evacuate refugees from Marble Mountain Air Facility.<ref name=Boston/>{{rp|77\u20138}} That night General Lanh, Deputy Commander of the RVNAF flew into the base and instructed General Khanh the RVNAF 1st Air Division commander to evacuate all flyable aircraft, 130 aircraft would be evacuated while some 180, including 33 [[Cessna A-37 Dragonfly|A-37s]], were abandoned.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lavalle|first=A|title=USAF Southeast Asia Monograph Series Volume III, The Vietnamese Air Force 1951\u201375|publisher=Office of Air Force History|year=1985|url=https://media.defense.gov/2010/Oct/13/2001330009/-1/-1/0/AFD-101013-043.pdf|isbn=0912799285|page=76}}</ref>\n\nThe PAVN attack began on the morning of 28 March with an artillery barrage on the city, probing attacks quickly penetrated the ARVN defenses, and the fragile ARVN discipline collapsed and soldiers began to desert their positions and seek refuge for themselves and their families. On the night of 28 March General Tr\u01b0\u1edfng received intelligence that an all-out PAVN assault against the city would commence the next morning and he decided to abandon Da Nang and ordered his forces to move to beaches for evacuation by sea.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|327\u20138}}\n\nOn the morning of 29 March, 2 World Airways [[Boeing 727]]s flew from Saigon to Da Nang to attempt to pick up more refugees. When the first 727 landed at Da Nang AB it was mobbed, 270 people pushed into the plane, all but 3 were ARVN. As the aircraft attempted to take off it was hit by a grenade which jammed the flaps and the main runway was blocked by trucks and the pilot instead took off from a taxiway. A number of ARVN hung onto the undercarriage and in the wheel wells, preventing the retraction of the landing gear, 4 of them survived the flight back to Saigon.<ref name=Boston/>{{rp|81\u20132}}\n\nThe PAVN entered the outskirts of Da Nang by mid-morning on 29 March and by the afternoon were in complete control of the city.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|328}} On 7 April the first VPAF transport aircraft began landing at Da Nang AB to support PAVN operations further south.<ref name=Veith/>{{rp|366}} In mid-April the VPAF formed the Quyet Thang (\"Determined to Win\") Squadron at Da Nang AB and began preliminary training of pilots on captured RVNAF A-37s, the squadron would carry out the [[Bombing of Tan Son Nhut Air Base]] on 28 April.<ref>{{cite book|last=Boniface|first=Roger (2008)|title=MiGs over North Vietnam: The Vietnam People's Air Force in Combat, 1965\u201375|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2008|isbn=9780811706964|pages=155\u20136}}</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n*On 16 March 1970 a U.S. Navy [[Lockheed EC-121 Warning Star|EC-121 Warning Star]] crashed on landing. The aircraft struck a hangar and caught fire killing 22 of the 31-man crew.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/reports/images.php?img=/images/1683/168300010812.pdf|title=Headquarters MACV Monthly Summary March 1970|publisher=Headquarters United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam|date=11 July 1970|accessdate=15 March 2020|pages=34-5}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{Air Force}}\n*{{Marine Corps}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Da Nang Air Base}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XYavDV00k8Y] Video of Danang Air Base from 1965 to 1970\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0BoHFCwCIIQ] Video of Danang Air Base from 1968\u20139\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Da Nang]]\n[[Category:Installations of the United States Air Force in South Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Military installations closed in 1975]]\n[[Category:Installations of the United States Army in South Vietnam]]\n", "name_user": "Mztourist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUSMC use", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Da_Nang_Air_Base"}
